{
  "answer": "**Chapter 47 of the *Kātyāyana Smṛti*** (also known as Katyayana Smriti) is titled \"The Measure of Interest\" and covers regulations on maximum interest rates for loans on various commodities.[^1]\n\nIt states that the principal lent by creditors is generally receivable as double (with further interest calculable if not repaid). Specific limits include:\n- Double the principal for gems, pearls, corals, gold, silver, cotton, silk, and wool.\n- Eight-fold for oils, liquors, ghee, molasses, and salt.\n- Five-fold for base metals.\n- Eight-fold for land, which must be repaid \"immediately.\"[^2]\n\nThese rules are referenced with verse markers like // K_509 // through // K_512 //.\n\n[^1]: Kātyāyana, *Kātyāyana Smṛti*, [Chapter 47 (translation)](/works/unknown-katyayana-smrti-1e06d2/47/translation/).\n\n[^2]: Specific passages include [p-16d029](/works/unknown-katyayana-smrti-1e06d2/47/translation/#p-16d029), [p-2acf4a](/works/unknown-katyayana-smrti-1e06d2/47/translation/#p-2acf4a), [p-bfebbd](/works/unknown-katyayana-smrti-1e06d2/47/translation/#p-bfebbd), and [p-d4145c](/works/unknown-katyayana-smrti-1e06d2/47/translation/#p-d4145c).",
